🌱 SPRING IoC – COMPLETE FLOW (XML BASED)

1️⃣ Creating Spring IoC Container

Main Class

ApplicationContext context =
        new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("spring.xml");

What Spring Does

Reads spring.xml

Creates objects (beans)

Injects dependencies

Manages lifecycle

👉 Developer never uses new keyword

2️⃣ Simple Bean Class (POJO)
package com.nit;

public class Demo {

    private int id;
    private String name;

    // setter injection
    public void setId(int id) {
        this.id = id;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    // constructor injection
    public Demo(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }

    public int getId() {
        return id;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}


✔ No Spring API
✔ Pure Java class = Bean

3️⃣ Creating Beans in spring.xml
<bean id="demo1" class="com.nit.Demo"/>
<bean id="demo2" class="com.nit.Demo"/>


✔ Same class → multiple objects
✔ Each <bean> = one object

4️⃣ Setter Injection (Primitive / String)
<bean id="demo" class="com.nit.Demo">
    <property name="id" value="1"/>
    <property name="name" value="Manoj"/>
</bean>

Flow

Object created

setId(1)

setName("Manoj")

✔ Optional dependency
✔ Flexible

5️⃣ Constructor Injection (Primitive / String)
<bean id="demo" class="com.nit.Demo">
    <constructor-arg index="0" value="2"/>
    <constructor-arg index="1" value="Nithin"/>
</bean>


✔ Mandatory dependency
✔ Object fully initialized

6️⃣ Object (Reference) Injection
Step 1: Dependent Class
package com.nit;

public class Address {

    private String city;

    public void setCity(String city) {
        this.city = city;
    }

    public String getCity() {
        return city;
    }
}

Step 2: Target Class
package com.nit;

public class Demo {

    private int id;
    private String name;
    private Address address;

    public void setId(int id) {
        this.id = id;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void setAddress(Address address) {
        this.address = address;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println(id + " " + name + " " + address.getCity());
    }
}

Step 3: spring.xml (Setter Reference Injection)
<bean id="addr" class="com.nit.Address">
    <property name="city" value="Hyderabad"/>
</bean>

<bean id="demo" class="com.nit.Demo">
    <property name="id" value="1"/>
    <property name="name" value="Manoj"/>
    <property name="address" ref="addr"/>
</bean>

Rule

value → primitives

ref → object

7️⃣ Constructor Reference Injection
<bean id="addr" class="com.nit.Address">
    <property name="city" value="Bangalore"/>
</bean>

<bean id="demo" class="com.nit.Demo">
    <constructor-arg index="0" value="2"/>
    <constructor-arg index="1" value="Nithin"/>
    <constructor-arg index="2" ref="addr"/>
</bean>

8️⃣ Single Interface → Multiple Implementations
Interface
package com.nit;

public interface PaymentService {
    void pay();
}

Implementation 1
public class CardPayment implements PaymentService {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Payment using Card");
    }
}

Implementation 2
public class UpiPayment implements PaymentService {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Payment using UPI");
    }
}

Dependent Class
public class PaymentProcessor {

    private PaymentService paymentService;

    public void setPaymentService(PaymentService paymentService) {
        this.paymentService = paymentService;
    }

    public void process() {
        paymentService.pay();
    }
}

Manual Injection (No autowire)
<bean id="card" class="com.nit.CardPayment"/>
<bean id="upi" class="com.nit.UpiPayment"/>

<bean id="processor" class="com.nit.PaymentProcessor">
    <property name="paymentService" ref="upi"/>
</bean>


✔ Loose coupling
✔ Runtime flexibility

9️⃣ autowire (Automatic Injection)
autowire="byName"
<bean id="paymentService" class="com.nit.CardPayment"/>

<bean id="processor" class="com.nit.PaymentProcessor"
      autowire="byName"/>


✔ Bean id = property name

autowire="byType" (Problem Case)
<bean class="com.nit.CardPayment"/>
<bean class="com.nit.UpiPayment"/>

<bean id="processor" class="com.nit.PaymentProcessor"
      autowire="byType"/>


❌ Error: Multiple beans of same type

🔟 primary (Solution for Multiple Beans)
<bean id="card" class="com.nit.CardPayment" primary="true"/>
<bean id="upi" class="com.nit.UpiPayment"/>

<bean id="processor" class="com.nit.PaymentProcessor"
      autowire="byType"/>


✔ Spring injects primary bean

autowire="constructor" + primary
<bean id="upi" class="com.nit.UpiPayment" primary="true"/>
<bean id="card" class="com.nit.CardPayment"/>

<bean id="processor" class="com.nit.PaymentProcessor"
      autowire="constructor"/>

🔑 FINAL INTERVIEW SUMMARY
Injection Types
Type	Use
Setter	Optional dependency
Constructor	Mandatory dependency
autowire Modes
Mode	Rule
byName	Bean id = property name
byType	Only one bean
constructor	Matches constructor args
primary

Resolves ambiguity

Used when multiple beans of same type exist

⭐ One-Line Interview Answer

Spring IoC creates and injects objects automatically, promoting loose coupling using interfaces, autowiring, and primary beans.